pro_note: Rainy River Peatland. Small ombrogeneous peatland about 180 ha in northwestern Ontario, Canada. The peatland has developed in a small, shallow basin lacking any surface outlets. The basin became available for peatland development after deglaciation and withdrawal of proglacial Lake Agassiz by ca. 9.5 ka BP, but it remained dry until ca. 4.6 ka BP (Belyea 1991). Peatland inception through primary peat formation.  NA
pro_veg_note: The modern vegetation consists of na open shrub peatland comunity with wel-developed microtopography of Sphagnum fuscum,S. angustifolium and Cladina lichens. ClosedPiceamarianaforestocursinsomeareasofthepeatland.

pro_note: Large peatland complex 30 km west of Thompson, Manitoba, in the Northern Study Area (NSA) of the Boreal Ecosystem and Atmosphere Study (BOREAS). Within the discontinuous PF. PF absent in the wetlands but present in elevated plateaus. Collapse bog: Open graminoid bog near the margin of a collapse scar formed by the collapse of a palsa and separated from the regional ground water table. Dominated by Sph. riparium (99% cover) with Carex paupercula and Vaccinium oxycocus (14 and 5% cover, respectively). Seasonal WT -1cm and peat pore water pH = 4   NA

pro_note: The plains that stretch out on either side of the mountains belong to the Arctic Lowlands physiographic region (Bostock, 1970). The numerous valleys formed in the lowlands were shaped during the successive Pleistocene glaciations (Klassen, 1993). Since the Holocene, these valleys developed highly dynamic biogeosystems rich in permafrost ground ice, peat, and aquatic environments. A terminal moraine, located about halfway between the actual glacier front and the seashore and sitting on marine clay, was 14Cdated to  9.8 k yrBP (Allard, 1996). Glacial retreat, accompanied by a marine trans15 gression phase, ended around 6 k yrBP. The outwash plain is bordered on both sides by a 3 to 5 m-thick terrace, criss-crossed by networks of tundra polygons associated with the formation of syngenetic ice wedges (Figs. 1d and 2a). Along the southern bank of the river, the upper portion of the terrace is composed of alternating organic (peat) and mineral (wind-blown sand and silt) material, which started to accumulate over glacio-fluvial sands and gravels around 3700 years ago (Fortier and Allard, 2004). These peaty loess deposits contain 25 excess pore ice (> 100% dry weight) and their gravimetric organic matter content can reach over 50 %. The active layer depth in such deposits generally ranges between 40 to 60 cm, and the maximum depth of permafrost on Bylot Island has been estimated to be over 400m (Smith and Burgess, 2000).  Permafrost terrace, glacier valley in Bylot Island - Eastern Canadian Arctic

3 notes sep by &: atmosphere & Gas collected with stainless steel probe described by Dinel et al. (1988). & Gas samples were separated into CO2 and CH4 cryogenically and CH4 was converted to CO2 by passing the gas through copper oxide heated to 850oC. Both gas samples were then analysed for 14C and 13C content using Accelerator Mass Spectrometry (AMS) at Isotrace, University of Toronto, Canada. All dates are corrected for isotopic fractionation to a d13C of -25permil. Water samples obtained during gas sampling were analysed at EIL for tritium after electrolytic enrichment by liquid scintillation counting with a counting error of  +- 0.8 TU.

3 notes sep by &: atmosphere & Water sampled from piezometers installed every 0.2 m depth. Using a variable-speed peristaltic pump, pore water was collected in to syringes with plungers removed, syringes were filled to overflowing, and plungers were reinserred [Chanton et al., 1995]. For CH4 concentration 13C-CH4, DIC concentration, 13-C DIC, and 14C-DIC, pore water was injected in to evacuated hypovials fitted with butyl rubber stoppers. These vials were immediately placed on ice for transport to a field station and then frozen for transport to Florida State University. & See section 3 for preparation and analytical of isotopes

For CH4 concentration 13C-CH4, DIC concentration, 13-C DIC, and 14C-DIC, pore water was injected in to evacuated hypovials fitted with butyl rubber stoppers. These vials were immediately placed on ice for transport to a field station and then frozen for transport to Florida State University. & See section 3 for preparation and analytical of isotopes

pro_veg_note: dwarf shrubs: Ledum spp, Vaccinium vitis-idaea, lichens and feather mosses including Pleurozium schreberi, and inter-hummock areas were dominated by relatively dry-adapted Sphagnum moss species including S. capillifolium and S. fuscum.
ist_notes: 3 notes sep by &: atmosphere & CO2: Passive diffusion in probes and chamber. CH4: Headspace extraction fron water samples in porespace and sealed bags for chambers with further processing in rig & Check paper

pro_treatment_note: warming of air, soil and permafrost
ist_notes: 3 notes sep by &: atmosphere & Soil pore space D14CO2 (hereafter referred to as soil profile D14CO2), d13CO2, and CO2 concentrations (five to six per treatment) were measured from gas samples collected during the last week of September 2009 from permanently installed soil gas wells located in each plot at 10 cm depth. The gas wells were made of stainless steel tubing (1/800 ID), which was perforated and covered with mesh at the bottom and extended aboveground 10cm to fittings with gas-tight stopcocks. Air was pumped from each gas well at 1.0 Lmin_1 for 1.5 min through a 13X molecular sieve to quantitatively trap CO2 & In the laboratory, the molecular sieve traps were heated to 625 1C to desorb CO2 (Bauer et al., 1992). Carbon dioxide was then purified and analyzed for d13C and D14C. Graphitized samples were sent to UC Irvine

pro_veg_note: tussockforming sedge,Eriophorum vaginatum, and deciduous shrub,Vaccinium uliginosum. Other common vascular plants includeCarex bigelowii,Betula nana,Rubus chamaemorus,Empetrum nigrum,Rhododendron subarcticum,V. vitisidaea,Andromeda polifolia, andOxycoccus microcarpus. Nonvascular plant cover is dominated byDicranumsp., feather moss (primarilyPleurozium schreberi), andSphagnumsp., as well as several lichen species (primarilyCladoniaspp.)

pro_veg_note: dominated by the tussock-forming sedge, Eriophorum vaginatum, with coexisting deciduous and evergreen shrubs, and an understory of mosses and lichens
ist_notes: 3 notes sep by &: atmosphere & Soil pore space CO2 was measured in gas sampling wells that have been installed at multiple depths in the soil profile (average sampling depth = 10-15 cm) at replicate locations per site (average number of unfrozen wells per site = 2-3). Stainless steel tubing, perforated and covered with mesh at the bottom, extends aboveground to fittings with gas-tight stopcocks. Air within the tubing equilibrates with soil pore CO2 concentrations and was sampled at several intervals during the winter months over the three-year period. Air was pumped from the well at 0.25L/min for 1 minute through a molecular sieve as described for the ecosystem respiration measurements & Check paper
